03973nam a22005535i 9780804773492DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047734927 a10.1515/97808047734922doi  a(DE-B1597)564697  a(OCoLC)1198929721  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0042802bisacsh04a860.9/11 aEgginton, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Theater of Truth :bThe Ideology of (Neo)Baroque Aesthetics /cWilliam Egginton. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Baroque as a Problem of Thought -- t1. Of Baroque Holes and Baroque Folds -- t2. How to Build a Baroque House (Cervantes, Master Architect) -- t3. The Theater of Truth -- t4. The Opacity of Language and the Transparency of Being: On Góngora's Poetics -- t5. The Corporeal Image and the New World Baroque -- t6. The Dream Life of Calderón and Borges -- t7. The World Well Dressed: The Later Cinema of Pedro Almodóvar -- tEpilogue: A New Distinction -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Theater of Truth argues that seventeenth-century baroque and twentieth-century neobaroque aesthetics have to be understood as part of the same complex. The Neobaroque, rather than being a return to the stylistic practices of a particular time and place, should be described as the continuation of a cultural strategy produced as a response to a specific problem of thought that has beset Europe and the colonial world since early modernity. This problem, in its simplest philosophical form, concerns the paradoxical relation between appearances and what they represent. Egginton explores expressions of this problem in the art and literature of the Hispanic Baroques, new and old. He shows how the strategies of these two Baroques emerged in the political and social world of the Spanish Empire, and how they continue to be deployed in the cultural politics of the present. Further, he offers a unified theory for the relation between the two Baroques and a new vocabulary for distinguishing between their ideological values.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAesthetics, Modern. 0aBaroque literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish American literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aSpanish American literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish literaturexHistory and criticismxClassical period, 1500-1700. 0aSpanish literatureyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aTruth (Aesthetics). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804773492zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804773492423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804773492.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles